Now I understand what the session did. Let me summarize:

The session made the analysis-only task pressure "landable" — meaning it's the implementation of a change to the evolution harness (`scripts/evolve.sh`) that stops retrying analysis-only task attempts. 

Previously, when an implementation agent's first attempt was "analysis-only" — meaning it produced no file changes, no terminal evidence — the harness would retry with a checkpoint ("PREVIOUS ATTEMPT WAS ANALYSIS-ONLY"). But this was wasteful: if the agent didn't produce any changes on the first attempt, a second attempt of the same analysis-heavy task was unlikely to succeed either.

The change:
1. In `scripts/evolve.sh`: When the first attempt is analysis-only (no file progress, no TASK_TERMINAL_EVIDENCE), the harness now stops the task instead of retrying. It writes a "blocked" note explaining the task should be replanned with narrower scope.
2. The checkpoint message was softened from "PREVIOUS ATTEMPT WAS ANALYSIS-ONLY" to "PREVIOUS ATTEMPT MADE NO FILE PROGRESS" — a more accurate description.
3. Tests in `test_task_lineage_feedback.py` were updated to match.

This is a harness evolution change — the harness getting smarter about when to retry vs. when to stop and ask for replanning. It tracks with the trajectory awareness feature (mentioned in CLAUDE.md) — the harness is learning from past sessions that analysis-only retries are wasteful.

The "no commits made" message in the user's context seems like it was auto-generated at session start and didn't get updated. The actual session did produce commits.

